Since \(N^2\) must be a divisor of \(8!\), the prime factorization of \(N\) must consist only of the primes that appear in \(8!\) and each prime must appear an even number of times in \(N\). Looking at the prime factorization of \(8!\), the highest power of 2 that can appear in \(N\) is \(2^3\), and the highest power of 3 that can appear is \(3^1\). The highest power of 5 and 7 that can appear is \(5^0\) and \(7^0\), respectively. Therefore, the greatest possible value of \(N\) is \(2^3 \times 3^1 = 24\).
